See ll Saggiatore, 20', dre, where he defends, as a possible explanation of comets, the theory that they are formed by exhalations from the earth, rising to a great height and reflecting the light of the Sun. The return of Halley’s Comet, nearly at the time predicted by him, in 1759, conclusively proved that these bodies belong to the solar, and not to the terrestrial system, and that, in the words of Seneca, they are ‘aeterna opera naturae.'
